            "When Jatin was twenty-six, something amazing happened. While returning home through a forest, a wild Royal Bengal tiger leapt at him. Jatin had no gun, only a Gurkha knife. Most people would have run. Jatin fought back. He grappled with the tiger, dodged its claws, and after a terrible fight, killed it — saving his village from a man-eater. The British government itself awarded him a silver shield, and from that day everyone called him 'Bagha Jatin' — Tiger Jatin. "
            "But Jatin's bigger fight was against a much larger animal — the British Empire. He joined the Anushilan Samiti and rose to lead a fearless faction called Jugantar. He believed in two things: physical strength and moral courage. He trained hundreds of young men in fitness, boxing, and tactics. His students said his eyes had a strange power — once he looked at you, you couldn't lie or be lazy again. "
            "In 1915, during the First World War, Bagha Jatin came up with a daring plan. The German government, then fighting Britain, was willing to send shiploads of weapons to India to help free her. Jatin would receive these weapons on a remote Bengal beach, distribute them across India, and lead a coordinated armed uprising. It would have shaken the British Empire to its core. "
